==English==
===Etymology===
From the [[English]] word [[wain]], meaning "wagon," and derived from the still older [[Carlswæn]], cognate with forms in other Germanic languages. It is possible that this common Germanic name originally meant the "men's wagon" (the churls' wagon) in contrast to the "women's wagon" (Ursa Minor). There is also a possibility that it was named after [[w:Charlemagne|Charlemagne]].

===Proper noun===
{{wikipedia|Big Dipper}}
'''[[Charles]]' [[wain|Wain]]'''

#{{constellation}}: A bright [[circumpolar]] [[asterism]] of the [[northern]] sky, said to resemble a [[wagon]] or [[cart]].  It is part of the [[constellation]] [[Ursa Major]] and includes the seven stars [[Dubhe]], [[Merak]], [[Phecda]], [[Megrez]], [[Alioth]], [[Mizar]], and [[Alkaid]].

====Quotations====
{{timeline|
1500s=1597|
1800s=1874|
1900s=1920}}
*'''1597''' — [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''[[s:The_First_Part_of_King_Henry_the_Fourth|1 Henry IV]] ii 1''
*:'''Charles' wain''' is over the new chimney, and yet our horse' not pack'd.
*'''1874''' — [[w:Thomas Hardy|Thomas Hardy]], ''[[s:Far from the Madding Crowd|Far from the Madding Crowd]]'' ch. vi
*:'''Charles's Wain''' was getting towards a right angle with the Pole star, and Gabriel concluded that it must be about nine o'clock.
*'''1920''' — [[w:H.P. Lovecraft|H.P. Lovecraft]], ''[[s:Polaris|Polaris]]''
*:Down from the heights reels the glittering Cassiopeia as the hours wear on, while '''Charles’ Wain''' lumbers up from behind the vapour-soaked swamp trees that sway in the night-wind.

